# CodingTutor .gitignore
#
# This project is intended for publication (Alex's GitHub). Third-party
# copyrighted material must NOT be committed unless a permissive license that
# allows redistribution is confirmed and recorded in REFERENCES.md.
#
# Rule of thumb: our OWN writing (notes, digests, references, code) is
# committed; third-party source artifacts (papers, books, media transcripts)
# stay local and git-ignored until their license is confirmed.
#
# To publish a specific permissively-licensed file anyway:
#   1. record its license in REFERENCES.md (§ Licensing & redistribution)
#   2. force-add it:  git add -f <path>

# --- Downloaded academic papers / books (gated or copyrighted by default) ---
materials/papers/*
!materials/papers/README.md

# --- Common third-party document / binary formats anywhere in the project ---
*.pdf
*.epub
*.mobi
*.doc
*.docx

# --- OS / editor cruft (root .gitignore also covers .DS_Store) ---
.DS_Store

# --- Third-party media transcripts (derivative of copyrighted audio) ---
# The "They Talk Tech" podcast transcript + its translation are derivative of
# copyrighted audio. Our committed digest/notes are our own writing and stay.
# NOTE: these two files are ALREADY TRACKED, so this ignore has no effect until
# they are untracked. If you want them local-only, run (keeps the local copy):
#   git rm --cached "materials/They Talk Tech transcript.txt" "materials/They Talk Tech transcript_EN.txt"
# and if the repo was already pushed, scrub history separately. See
# REFERENCES.md § Licensing & redistribution.
# Untracked 2026-07-15 via `git rm --cached` (German original); the EN
# translation was never committed. Both now git-ignored below.
materials/They Talk Tech transcript.txt
materials/They Talk Tech transcript_EN.txt
